All week as I’m watching people’s stories I’ll come to one and it’s mine and it confuses me and oh!…..IG made a reel from my stories and put it to a country music soundtrack and is suggesting I post it?! What the….? I guess it kinda makes me feel good that they don’t know everything about me. That I really don’t like country music. But anyways here’s this quilts birth story. We’re still in labor—somewhere around the transition stage. I’ve got this! Almost there!

It never feels like I’m getting things done in the moment because all my work happens so very slowly but in hindsight there it all is. Some highlights of 2022: 

🌱🌀 So many quilts! More than I’ve ever made in a year, most of which are yet to be revealed. 

🌱🌈 Colors! So many natural dye recipes refined and waiting for you. 

🌀 Losing both our beloved elderly dogs was certainly not a highlight but adopting two puppies was indeed. 

🌱🌼 A summer of growing dyestuffs. So many flowers! 

🌱🌀 Designing The Folk Garden quilt and pattern. 

🌱🕸️Cosmic geometric quilting which is becoming my trademark. Excited to show you more of that work soon. 

🌱📖 Oh and finishing my manuscript! The book is tentatively coming late summer/early fall of 2023. Getting closer ever day!!

Thanks for following along on all my adventures! Cheers and happy almost New Year!
🌱🌀🙏🏼

Deep thoughts with Sara B 🤓: 

“Farming has taught me everything. It has been my biggest influence. When I’m out in the field pulling weeds or hoeing and I hear the birds above me, the insects buzzing, I think about the worlds of microbes and mycelial networks at my feet. It’s a serious vibe. It’s a connection to nature and to the food I grow that I cannot describe in words. It’s something you have to experience to understand. I can pause to watch an ant colony in action and gain a better understanding of the world through the ants. When I see the generations of crops sprouting every spring and returning to the earth every fall it reminds me that I am only here for a short time, that I too am part of that infinite life and death earth cycle.”
Stripes are my only plan for 2023.

One of the questions asked after my Feedback Friday @botanicalcolors presentation this morning was something along the lines of: how do you deal with the feelings of vulnerability sharing your work and art? In my presentation I talked about how vulnerable it felt to first launch my quilts via my website and how scary that was. It really is scary to put your work out there because it’s basically an invitation for criticism in many ways but it’s also a leap that every artist or anyone wanting to try something new and different has to take. 
Last night I was helping my daughter with a history project she’s putting together about Georgia O’Keeffe and we were flipping through her autobiography (pictured above). She mentioned how Stieglitz hung her first show without her knowing and how upset she was because she felt so vulnerable and so not ready for anyone other than herself to see her work. But of course people loved her work and it helped her get over that hurdle. We all have to start at the beginning. Then later in the book she talked about how she would sit in the gallery each time her shows were hung and take it all in and form her own opinion about whether it was good or not and then consciously disregard all the flattery and criticism people had to say about it. Another stellar piece of advice! Just wanted to share those little bits and also encourage you to go for it if you’re thinking of putting something out there or making a change. Aim for the stars, you never know if it will lead to something unless you put it out there.

My friend Julius @houseofquinn wrote this gorgeous book called Modern Quilting: A contemporary guide to quilting by hand. If you’re like me and you’ve had your eye on it for a while I recommend making that leap and getting yourself a copy. It’s not only full of gorgeous natural light photography that accentuates all the yummiest hand quilted textures, but also contains 20 beautiful and practical projects. He covers all the basics of quilt making and beyond including tools and equipment, fabrics, color, and so many detailed techniques. I love seeing how other folks do basic techniques and Julius made beautiful, simple illustrations to demonstrate them, which I love. The book and projects are modern yet classic and timeless in all the best ways. As thorough as it is it also leaves plenty of room for the reader to expand on which is my favorite kind of book for sure. Well done Julius!

Due for an intro🌱🌞:
I’m Sara B, farmer, natural dyer, quilt maker, mama to 4 mostly grown ups. My husband Tom and I have been growing food for 26 years. We grow a lot of what we eat but also buy a lot from the store. We’re always striving to grow more and buy less. I’ve been a natural dyer for 20 years and made my first quilt 10 years ago. I’ve spent much of the last 17 years homeschooling my kids. This is my first year as a homeschool retiree and I’m enjoying putting my energy into being a full time artist. I’m in the final stages of writing a book with Abrams about natural dyes for cellulose fabrics specifically for quilts. It contains 20 specific color recipes and 10 projects and will be published this September which seems so far away yet so close. What a long strange trip it is to write a book and you know, just life in general. Thank you for your interest in what I share here! Please say hi and introduce yourself if you’re feeling it.🌱🌀

Let’s talk! I brought up the topic of question asking in my story yesterday and my DM’s are blowing up with Amens and 💯’s. I speak only for myself on this though ha:
If you see something here on my page and you have a question about how to do it, before messaging me please ask yourself “can I google this?” Googling it will just about always provide a better and more thorough answer than I could possibly type in a DM and I 💯don’t have time to answer every question. I used to feel bad about not answering the questions but I 💯 don’t feel a way about it anymore. Most of the time people don’t even take the time to introduce themselves when they ask something or to respond or even thank me when I do answer which is a whole other thing I could go on about lol. A lot of people are very considerate though and I see you too! 

I have a book coming this September which will answer so many of the questions I’m most frequently asked. I put aside my work for 13 months to work exclusively on this book and I’m beyond glad I did it! It helped me put my passion for growing and making into words and it helped me understand that my deepest passions are right there in growing and making things. It helped me figure out that those things are mainly what I want to spend my time doing and not so much in stopping to explain how I do all of it. I’m super proud of the book! I have no shame in saying it’s beautiful and I think you’ll agree that it’s a needed resource. 

Over the years I’ve shared some how-to stuff on my blog and here because I’m self taught which means I’ve learned by practice and experimentation but also by what others have so generously taken time to share. For that it’s important to me to share back, to reciprocate. I have some exciting workshops coming that are soon to be announced and the book and some smaller things. It’s all very exciting. Outside of this I’m spending most of my time growing and making so please do your part and google it if you have a question beyond what I’ve shared. If you have a question about a pattern or PDF you’ve purchased please don’t hesitate to ask away! Xxxxx

Seeds are tiny miracles of profound potential. Through the alchemical magic between soil, water and sunlight they transform to become food that nourishes us, fiber that clothes us or in this case beautiful color to feast our eyes upon. Imagine a pop culture of humans passionately focused on planting seeds and tending to plants via sustainable indigenous growing methods. A culture that understands and therefore appreciates the true value of food and fiber because of the tangible relationship we have with it. This paradigm shift begins when we plant seeds. 

🌱🌞I’m excited to offer a limited quantity of dye seeds which are available on the website. It’s easy to admire a finished quilt but important to remember that it began as seeds. It’s important to acknowledge all the beautiful natural processes that led up to it. Seeds are where so many things begin. 

🌱🌞Leave a comment for a chance to be gifted one packet of each of the five seed varieties I have available. As always only followers may leave a comment. I will announce the winner on Thursday. Remember to beware of scammers. I am the only one who will contact the winner. Do not respond to any accounts pretending to be me! 

*I can only ship seeds to the US. 

🌱🌞Let’s plant the future!

Sometimes people ask how I’m able to part with the quilts. Being a farmer helps. The process of planting seeds and caring for them for months which leads up to the final moment of harvest. A love for the processes of planting and tending and all the alchemy intertwined is what keeps farmers farming. The connection. The experience! Making a quilt feels the same. The joy is in making it—each step that leads up to the last binding stitch. Then it’s sent off and I get to begin again. 🌱🙏🏼 The quilt is a beautiful bi-product of the processes. It’s only with me for a short time but I’m left with the experience of making it forever.

Another cute dress made from the book A Year of Sewing with Nani Iro. I love the patterns in this book and this wonderful English translation version of the book can be found @zakkaworkshop 

Folks always ask about the skill level required for these patterns. They vary and each pattern is rated by difficulty in the book. There are a few easy ones and then they get more difficult. Generally speaking if you’re brand new to sewing I don’t recommend this as a starting place. Start with some independent pattern maker patterns that explain each and every step and then work your way up to these. But do get yourself a copy of this awesome book because you’re gonna want it once you’re ready for it! 

The fabric is Japanese but that’s all I remember about it. It’s been in my stash for a while. 

Some independent pattern makers which I’ve tried and love:
@sewliberated @madebyrae @annaallenclothing 
Patterns such as these offer very thorough instructions.
Been working on these little quilts between irrigating and tending to crops. Totally going to try to stay up past 9:30 tonight to finish. LOL 🤞🏼🤞🏼🤞🏼
Quit the gym and join the hoerobics revolution! Guaranteed fresh homegrown food as a bi product of all the working out. Join today! 💪🏼🌱🌀
Another Sunday, another garment sewn. Farmer Pants! Slide to see the pattern info. Made from a thrifted tablecloth 💪🏼.

Been quiet here lately due to being slammed with farm work and workshop prep (NY here I come next week @katrinarodabaugh !!) and custom pieces and finishing up some pieces. Newsletter subscribers check your inboxes. Hopefully it didn’t go to spam this time 🌱✌🏼🌞

🌱🌞AVAIALABLE—slides 2 & 4 on the website🌞🌱

I released a few new smaller works to the website yesterday. I’ll post links to my story if you want to check them out!

It’s a book, a REAL book!! Slide for a show and tell of a first little peek. I’ll share a little bit more every so often in the weeks leading up to the September 26 publication date. Thanks for the pre-orders and to all who plan to order! What a feeling to hold it and I can’t wait for you to hold it too!
First Black Knight Scabiosa bloom and cutest photo bomber! Thanks to @grandprismaticseed for this magical seed. I am smitten!

Party favors! I made these cutie pincushions from a free pattern I found online. I’ll post a link in my stories if you’re interested. I used my naturally dyed scraps but I have so many this barely made a dent. 🌱🌸

Another revolution around the sun and here I find myself again in summer on this speck of earth farm harvesting flowers that magically burst forth from seeds. Is this real or a dream? Something I ask myself every time I’m in the garden.

I rarely leave the farm but tomorrow I catch the first plane out to make my way to NY to teach a workshop with @katrinarodabaugh in her beautiful studio. Can’t wait! Whose clean toes are these even? I’ll send some postcards via my stories 🌱

Just feeling grateful today. For the amazing weekend teaching a beautiful group of folks with @katrinarodabaugh and for the flowers I’m harvesting today. You know how all the plants in the garden look so big when you’ve been away for a sec? 
🌱🙏🏼🌼

I don’t know how to say this or even what’s too much to share here but here goes. The other day I was attacked by a super aggressive bee colony here on the farm. They got me so good that I had to take an ambulance ride to the hospital and it really almost didn’t end well. I can’t tell you how humbled and grateful I am to be here still with my people and puppies and the flowers. What a trip it is to be alive and to be human. The bee’s were transported to another location because if I get stung again it’ll send me back to a critical state. For now this is my flower harvest outfit while the last lingering attack bees are angrily flying around trying to sting us. I really want to be clear that it’s super unusual for bees to behave this way. We’ve kept hives for 15 years and have never seen anything like this. Despite it all I still say save the bees!  But also be careful my fellow beekeeper friends.🌱🙏🏼❤️ 🐝

🌱🌞Pre-order now from your favorite book seller! 🌱🌞

Publication date is  9/26/23!

Sharing section 1 from my book with you today. There are 4 sections and 4 weeks till publication so I’ll be sharing a new section every weekend. I’ll put a link to pre-order in my story. Thanks for all the pre-orders so far! Section 1 is all about the pre-dye alchemy that needs to happen in order to create lasting naturally dyed color on cellulose fabrics such as cotton, linen and hemp. It talks all about tannins and mordant and how I use tannins not only as an alchemy but as an opportunity to build color foundations. I hope it will enlighten you and inspire you to broaden your palettes and give you freedom and confidence in the mordanting process. 🥰 
Never mind the  mushrooms growing out of my head!

🍂🐑WORKSHOP!🐑🍂

🌱🕸️Before I discovered quilt making I was really into sheep and wool and hand spinning and knitting. It was in fact my flock of sheep that originally inspired me to dive deeper into the alchemy of natural dyes. 

🌱🐑 So when @stellamariabaer invited me to teach a workshop at her ranch in the Santa Fe region this October I didn’t hesitate to say yes! 

🌱🎟️We still have tickets available and would love for you to join us at Stella’s beautiful @moon_horse_ranch for 2 days of hand spinning on drop spindles and a (wheel or two). 

🌱🌈We will also set up some dye pots and dye some skeins with plants foraged from the desert and I’ll bring some flowers from my dye garden as well. 

🌱🌞This is the same weekend as the solar eclipse and I can’t think of a better place to witness that than New Mexico. I hope to see you there!

🌱🎟️To purchase tickets head over to @moon_horse_ranch where you’ll find a link in her bio.

Dusted off my wheel and am working on spinning and dyeing some samples for the Fleece & Flower workshop I’m teaching with @stellamariabaer at @moon_horse_ranch this October. Please join us for a dreamy day of spinning and natural dyes in the desert. I’ll post a link to join in my stories but you can also find one on the @moon_horse_ranch profile page.

Happy Saturday! I’m sharing some section 2 excerpts from Farm & Folk Quilt Alchemy with you today. This section shares all my favorite dye formulas including my recipe for achieving a true black on cellulose fabric. Just a few more weeks to go now! Next week I’ll share section 3 and you’ll get to see the quilt patterns that I’ve had to keep secret all this time. In the meantime I’ll just be over here trying not to get too excited and nervous about this book being out in the world. 🎉

Wool from my old sheep spun up and ready for the dye pot. Slowly I will spin more and slowly the yarn will become a sweater. This beautiful process rooted in connection to the land and to sheep has revealed to me the true value of clothing. The slow processes of sustainable production from seed to table from sheep to garment is the ancient future I long for.

Enjoy a little peek into this beautiful informative book 
In Pursuit of Color
 by Lauren MacDonald of @working_cloth 

From fungi to fossil fuels: uncovering the origins of the world’s most famous dyes.

Congratulations Lauren!

My to do list is crazy these days and I’ve been too busy to share much. Today began with an indigo harvest and ferment set up, then harvesting safflower then a zoom meeting. Then a quick pop over to the studio to work on a custom piece, then some work on the dye kits I’m putting together. Then a quick go to town to pick up my girl. It feels good to sit right here right now with some spinning I need to get through. Then off to make dinner and feed the dogs who are giving me a stare down like no other and then some needle turn appliqué for a deadline custom piece I’m working on before bed. It’s a lot but it’s all good stuff and I love it but it’s a lot but I wouldn’t rather be doing anything. And now for a big poppa quote “it’s all good baby baby”. 🌱🤌🏼

Homegrown indigo pigment OMG! 🌱🌀✨⚡️

(P.S. gonna take a week or two off from sharing the next sections of my book. )

There are still a few tickets available for the natural dye workshop I’m teaching in Portland this month on September 23-24 with @portlandmqg at Craft Emporium. We will be dyeing this fun autumn palette. I hope to see you there! I’ll put a link to the ticket sales in my story. 🌱🌀

I’ve been bad at documenting it this summer but I’ve been spending so much time in the field harvesting dye flowers. Here’s a little taste of a kit I will be offering in the coming weeks. I’ll have 2 kits to offer this time around, both of which will come with all the supplies and materials you need.  I’m excited to share more soon you guys! 🌱✋🏼🌼🤚🏼🌱

I’m working on so many projects right now my head is spinning 😵‍💫 but it’s all good. I’m excited to tell you more soon. Tomorrow I’m planning on sharing section 3 (the quilts and projects!) of my book so look for that post if you fancy a peek.

Happy Saturday! We’re just over 2 weeks from publication day. Here’s a peek into Section 3, the project section, which covers the alchemy of transforming naturally dyed fabric into quilts. It was so difficult for me to keep this work secret as I made it. You know I love sharing my process and I’m so happy to get to share these projects with you today. You can pre-order Farm & Folk Quilt Alchemy from your favorite book seller worldwide. I can hardly-barely wait to see your interpretations of these patterns!

What to do with spare quilt blocks? I wrote a tutorial on the blog to share my favorite way to sew a block onto a garment. I’ll put a link in my story and will be sure to save it to my tutorial highlight! Tag me if you use the tutorial so I can see your quilt clothes!

How cute are this years flower packs? I feel like the flowers are totally waving and batting their eyelashes! 

Can’t wait to tell you more about this seasons flower launches. There will be a few. They will be be fun and exciting. Newsletter subscribers will be notified first so sign up on my website if you aren’t already subscribed.

I’m having a sale over on the website to get ready for all the new dyes and quilts I will be offering in the next couple weeks. 
🌱🫶🏼Use the code 🫶🏼🌱
 MAKEWAY
  on the checkout page 
  to save 20% on all orders

There are a few dye variety packs left from last season. If you want to make The Folk Garden quilt you will need the variety pack, the flower recipe PDF, and The Folk Garden pattern PDF. 

There are links to the sale in my stories. The sale runs till 9/18 at midnight.

Thank you so much for supporting our small family farm ! 

P.S. 💌
My newsletter subscribers receive news of any new offerings the day before I announce it here. You can sign up to receive my newsletter on the website. 🙏🏼

This week in a nutshell. It looks calm maybe but in reality I’m not doing great at keeping up with everything I’ve taken on this season. I need 3 more of me!

🌱🫶🏼Thank you for your orders yesterday. My 20% off sale is going on through 9/18

Making yarn from our old sheep. We don’t have sheep these days but I still have lots of their Corriedale and CVM wool to work with. Almost ready to dye the skeins I’ve been making. Can’t wait!
I will try to share section 4 of the book later today but for now I’m headed out to the field to begin a big dye flower harvest. 🍂🐏

I’m over the moon today to be featured on the @floretflower blog. The way that Erin Benzakein uplifts and shares the work and stories of others is so inspiring to me. She has written 3 beautiful books and has a show on the Magnolia Network called Growing Floret, all of which I highly recommend. There’s a link in my story to the interview where you can leave a comment to enter to win a copy of my book and the wall hanging featured in this post (scroll). Many thanks to Erin and the team at Floret for this beautiful feature. 
🌱🫶🏼🌱🌸

Feeling very grateful for the opportunity to be a speaker and teacher last weekend for @portlandmqg 
It was definitely a huge step outside of my comfort zone when I agreed to take this workshop on but I’m so glad I did. I have grown, I can do these things. ❤️ 
Thanks to all the wonderful people who planned and organized the event and to all the wonderful students. I’m returning home with a full heart and feeling ready to launch my book TOMORROW 🌱🫶🏼

Photos by @notablenormalcy and @pdxcupcake 🌱🙏🏼

((Winners have been announced!))
🍂🫶🏼 G I F T A W A Y 🫶🏼🍂
⚡️Happy publication day!!⚡️
This book is 2 1/2 years in the making. How surreal to see it officially going out into the world today! I poured my everything into these pages and I sure hope you will find something within that inspires you. Something that you can expand upon and perhaps share in the future🌀

Today I’m gifting 2 copies! 
To enter:

🍂Leave a kind comment. (My page always only accepts comments from followers so you’ll have to follow to comment.)

🍂I’ll announce the winners on Friday via direct message. My one and only account is blue check verified so block and report any accounts pretending to be me and do not give anyone your financial info!

🍂This gift away is not sponsored or associated with Instagram. By entering you agree to Instagram’s terms of use.

🍂 US entries only unless you’re willing to pay shipping. 🙏🏼

My buddies at @botanicalcolors invited me to do a Takeover Tuesday with them today. Here’s one of the videos I made to share over there and you can head to their stories to get a peek at a fun project from my book. 
Thanks so much to Botanical Colors and all of you good folks out there. Together we are creating a new culture!

These are the super fun dye kits that will be available very soon! One is a beginner dye kit for folks who want to try natural dyeing for the first time. The other is a dye + make your own star quilt block kit. They both come with my homegrown flowers and all the instructions and materials you will need. I’m doing a limited run on these so sign up for my newsletter to be the first to receive the news when they drop. You can subscribe on my website.

Finally getting around to sharing section 4! This section totally breaks down how you can make a quilt on your own from beginning to end without a pattern. I explain how to dissect traditional blocks and make them on your own in any size you desire. There are tutorials for the most common shapes found within blocks, a straight and on-point setting, a quilt back tutorial, a quilt sandwich, a hand quilting/tying tutorial, a binding tutorial and so much more! I wrote this book not only for you but for me. I’m so happy to have all these basics all in one easy to access place!

Please join me this Saturday 9/30 at noon mountain time for an Instagram live sesh to celebrate the book launch. We can do a live ask me anything (book related or not) and I will sign any books that are purchased on my website throughout the hour. Hope you can join! 🥂
⏰ There’s a link in my story to set a reminder if you wish.

Are you guys ready to see the quilts I made for the book? Oh man, it was so difficult for me to keep them secret! This is the first pattern which explains not only how to make a quilt if you’re a brand new beginner but there’s a color study element to this pattern as well. Choose a color formula from section 2 and dye 6 depths of shade from 1 dye pot. Leave it as is or modify it, then dye a background color and make this quilt. Learn how to not only achieve a gradation but also how to use it in your work. This one is super fun! The patchwork is simple but the dye work gives this piece a complex feeling. 
I’m looking forward to sharing some more quilts from the book soon!

Sorry there are no captions! There is a captioned version saved to the “my book” story highlight.
Thanks to all who joined our live ask me anything. Sorry for the abrupt ending! I lost my internet connection. Hope you’re enjoying the weekend ❤️

Gradations of each of the 20 color formula recipes from my book. Natural dyes shining bright on cellulose fabrics! 
🌱✋🏼🌈🤚🏼🌱

#naturaldyes #naturaldyeing #plantdyes #farmandfolkquiltalchemy

I’m excited to be featured in the Colorado issue of @quiltfolk magazine! This photo shoot by @melanie.zacek + @kimberleezacek was so fun and they did such an incredible job! My daughter and I will treasure these images forever!🌱🙏🏼See slide 2 for a 20% off coupon code you can use to purchase a copy. I’ll put a link in my stories and save this feature to my “features” story highlight.
This seasons dye flower varieties. I’m getting close to finishing these beginner dye kits. Just need a sunny morning to create some photos! Can’t wait to share this magic with you.

Another day closer with these kits. I’ve been spending so much time working on them. There are so many steps to these kind of projects and in my head it will go fast but in reality it takes forever. I’m feeling like I’m to the point where I should maybe hire someone but it feels so scary and can I even afford it? Are there any resources or books you can guide me to about how to grow a small creative business? 🌱🙏🏼

Introducing another quilt featured in my book The Tumbleweed Quilt. This pattern introduces the reader to 3 foundational shapes that many traditional quilt blocks are made from. Once you learn to make these shapes in any custom size you can make so many different blocks without a pattern. The book also provides recipes to dye all these colors. This quilt will be available to purchase in my shop soon and you can read the story behind it in my book and on my website soon.

A huge thank you to everyone who purchased dye kits today. I announced the launch last evening to my newsletter subscribers, it went live at noon and sold out in less than an hour. So sorry to those who missed this round but I will launch another round at holiday season. Maybe we’ll do a preorder? I’ll talk more about it as we get closer. 
THANK YOU SO MUCH FOR SUPPORTING OUR SMALL FAMILY FARM!! 🌱🫶🏼🌱🩵

Thanks again for the dye kit love on Friday! We’re working on another batch that will be ready for holiday season. I’m thinking about offering them via pre-order this time around. Do you prefer pre-order or ready to buy? Please let me know your thoughts in the comments. 

These new dye flower varieties are available now in my shop along with all the varieties I offered last season:
🫶🏼rudbeckia 
🩵black hollyhock
🍂black scabiosa 
🌞dyer’s chamomile
I’ll put links in my story!

📙Oh and I also restocked signed copies of my book.

Saying goodbye to the Jackrabbit quilt today. I’ve never loved a quilt more. 🙏🏼This one feels like the most authentic quilt I’ve ever made. The story behind it and the cosmic hand stitches which were totally unplanned as though they came from my soul. I’ll share the flat lay photo of it tomorrow. 
My daughter took these photos for me when she was just 13, in late July on a rare evening when the light was perfectly diffused. The first photo appears on the back cover of my book. These stories and moments in time that cause us to pause and take it all in and reflect on how beautiful it is to be alive. That’s what this quilt is to me. You can read about it on my website in its shop listing, and in my book where you can also find this pattern and all the natural dye formulas to make it. 
I ‘m so grateful to send this one and all the others out into the world. 🍂🫶🏼🩵🌞

The Jackrabbit Quilt:
front——>back

Subtle differences are profound on a dark background. 🍂🖤

a dream come true to host Sara Buscaglia @farmandfolk for a Fleece Spinning and Natural Dye Workshop at @moon_horse_ranch this past weekend. thank you Sara for teaching us the alchemy of dying with plants and minerals. and thank you to everyone who came, it was a joy to be with you all, dying yarn in the field 🐏🐴✨🌼

I sent out an email this morning disclosing the date and time of the beginner dye kit presale launch. If you are a subscriber and you’re not seeing it, check your spam box. If you are not a subscriber and you want to receive notice of the sale when it goes live, subscribe now because I have an email scheduled to go out the moment the sale goes live. This presale batch of kits will ship late November/early December in time for holiday gifting. Thanks so much in advance for supporting our small family farm and business!!
🍂🫶🏼🩵

I’m so grateful the tomatoes held out till I could get them put up in jars. I’ll have 105 quarts by days end. Tomorrow I’ll move on to sauce. Stocking the pantry shelves with homegrown goodness is a very satisfying feeling!
It’s a real honor to be featured in Quilt Folk issue 28, the Colorado issue! Check it out and use code SaraQF28 to purchase a copy over at the @quiltfolk site 🫶🏼🍂🩵

🌻editing to say: the beginner dye kits are sold out but there are still quilt block kits available!

I launched the preorder kits yesterday. Thanks to my newsletter subscribers for your orders! There are a few beginner natural dye kits left and a handful of quilt block kits left. I will close the preorder tomorrow morning so I can order supplies and get these kits put together and shipped to you. Please get your orders in today if you want a kit. I will offer a very limited amount of ready to buy kits when these preorders are ready to ship. My goal is to ship this batch the last week of November or first week of December, in time for holiday gifting. Thanks so much for supporting our small family farm! 🫶🏼🍂🩵

The dye flowers have taken over my studio. I’m looking forward to packing them up and sending them off to you! Thanks so much for your orders that directly support our small organic family farm. If you ordered items besides the preorder kits they are being mailed today with the exception of books because I’m waiting on my next shipment. The books will ship as soon as I receive them. Thanks for your patience! We hope to ship the dye kit preorders by the last week of November. Thanks again!

Oh and please join me and my good buddy @heidi.parkes tomorrow at 11am mountain time for an Instagram live session. We’ll talk about quilts of course but also lots of other fun topics and you guys can ask questions too. Hope to see you then! 🍂🩵🫶🏼

Thanks to all who joined this live sesh with my friend @heidi.parkes and here’s the recording if you missed it. We talked for a super long time about our future plans and so many other topics. Thanks Heidi and everyone!
Finally finally finally getting back to some studio work and gosh does it ever feel good!
My version of needle turn appliqué with big visible stitches. I cheat and roll the hem with my fingers often.

I’m giving my old studio a makeover. This will be my sewing studio again and my big studio will be where all the messy things happen. A place to bring in and cure the dye flower harvest, a working dye studio and a place to pack orders that need to be shipped. I’m super excited to spend the winter here in this warm and cozy passive solar space making quilts, writing, and making tea on the fire.

Getting there with the new old studio. Still need to move the wood stove and design wall back over. The paint is lime paint for those asking. I had it mixed in a custom color to match the adobe colored exterior stucco. I’m happy with it! It makes the space feel warm. The walls were previously white and it was so bright with the south facing passive solar windows that it hurt my eyes. 
The old studio is a big mess but it will be fun to build some workbenches and all the things necessary to make it function better as a natural dye studio and packing facility. I’ll share more details once I’ve settled in and have everything put back together.

“Mycelium is incredibly tiny fungal threads that are interconnected to form massive mycelial networks or “wood wide webs”. Water, nutrients, and minerals are transferred through this amazing network, and trees are able to communicate with each other through it. Mycelium is a beautiful example of interconnectedness. The white stars in this quilt represent individual trees that are connected by a mycelial network of tiny intricate fabric scraps. “
(An excerpt from my book)

This quilt is available on my website and the pattern and color recipes can be found in my book Farm & Folk Quilt Alchemy.

Sometimes I build things. It’s just about the same process as sewing things—measure and cut and put it together—I just hurt myself more and say waaay more swear words. My packing facility is coming right along. Just in time to get your pre-orders packed and mailed off to you 🍂🙏🏼
My newest creation! A block printing table on casters. Now I can attempt to make all my block printing dreams come true.

Did you hear? I’m super excited to be teaching a natural dye and make your own tiny quilt workshop with @botanicalcolors this February 9-11 at their headquarters in Seattle. It’s going to be such fun and I hope you can join us. Tickets are going fast but there are still a few left. I posted links to tickets and more information about this event in my stories. Hope to see you there! 🍂🩵🫶🏼

New blog post! 

I finally got around to writing the long promised plant fiber history acknowledgment to expand on the one I wrote on page 6 of my book. It inevitably morphed into so much more than a historical acknowledgment. Perhaps writing it at the onset of the biggest consumer frenzy event of the year had something to do with it. 

And oh the irony! I also wrote a newsletter that will go out tomorrow announcing the date and time of my dye kit launch. The dichotomy of writing a post about prioritizing need over want and then writing a newsletter to sell my homegrown products to support my small business. It’s all so much! Subscribe to my newsletter if you want to hear my thoughts about it and I’ll post a link to the blog post in my stories. 

Oh and I updated the link tree on my profile page as well so you can find links to everything mentioned above there as well.

I got all your dye kit pre-orders packed today and I’ll drop them to the post office on Monday! Thanks so much you guys! These will be in your hands soon and I hope you’ll tag me when you’re working with them so I can see the magic happen. 🌱⚡️🌈

I launched a small batch of ready to purchase kits this morning and they’re going fast but there’s still some left. This will be the last chance to get them for a while because I reallllly want to/need to get back to making quilts. Get ‘em while they’re hot buddies and thanks again! Enjoy the process!

When I wrote my book the editors and I went over the text an unfathomable amount of times but alas a couple mistakes have been brought to my attention. Please grab your copy and a pencil and mark these changes. My humble apologies! I will file this in my story highlights and I also published a blog post which should be easy to find if you do a web search for “farm & folk quilt alchemy errata.

Finding things (like my homegrown indigo pigment!) as I work on rethinking this space to get it up and running as a dye and block printing studio, a place to cure and store my flower harvest, and a year round dye studio. Getting closer every day!

An Ode to Summer quilt. A medicine to carry you through this cold, dark, dormant season. 

This quilt and pattern are featured in my book. I used this pattern as an opportunity to introduce the flying goose shape and also to explain how to dye several yards of fabric the same depth of shade. This green color was achieved with Osage Orange and the recipe can be found in the side note on page 57. 

This quilt is currently available in my shop. I’ll post a link in my story. Swipe to see the back and also the groovy hand stitching pattern that unintentionally looks a bit like crop circles. 

“The seeds that were silent all burst into bloom, and decay. And night comes so quiet it’s close on the heels of the day.”
Jerome Garcia + Robert Hunter

Screening seeds today. I’ll have some pretty little seeds for you soon. 🌱⚡️

I’m getting so close to wrapping up the farm work and studio renovations. Tomorrow is a dye day! It feels so good to accomplish the big things so I can move on to the big creative things that are bubbling. ⚡️

Madder root pink is such a yummy color!

🫶🏼644 grams of homegrown indigo pigment! 🌱✋🏼🔵🤚🏼🌱

⚡️This past season was my first time growing this plant. My first time even meeting her! From planting the seeds in early spring, to harvesting the leaves and extracting the pigment in late summer, to finally grinding the dry pigment today to store it in this jar. A magical connection to source. Time to set up an indigo vat! 

🌱Thanks to @thedogwooddyer who guided me through this process. You can find her fresh indigo workshop on her website. 🌀
.

I spent a whole day plucking safflower petals from their spiky flower heads. They’re brutal to handle! They’re such pretty flowers but yeah so spiky and next year I’m gonna be finding some special gloves to harvest them. At the end of the day I had thrashed up hands and about 2/3 of a small bucket full of petals. Not a dye that would make sense for me to sell but I’ll have to make something special with it.
Feeling mighty fine to get all the things up off the floor and sorted and packed and in their special places. It feels like a country store and it is I guess. You need some dye flowers? I’ve got em!
